Barings Corporate Investors (NYSE:MCI) Sees Unusual Trading Volume in Its Shares 












































 Finance DailyDaily markets, commodities, personal finance and economic newsBarings Corporate Investors (NYSE:MCI) Sees Unusual Trading Volume in Its Shares
July 25, 2017 By Ted Blackburn Tweet
        Advertisement



401 shares changed hands in the last trading session.  Shares saw a steep decrease in trading volume of 97.03% under the normal average daily volume. 
 These firms have also modified their investment in MCI.   Barings LLC added to its ownership by buying 54,018 shares an increase of 32.6% from 12/31/2016 to 03/31/2017. Barings LLC controls 219,664 shares valued at $3,354,000. The total value of its holdings increased 33.8%. As of quarter end Ifp Advisors, Inc had bought 533 shares growing its position 100.4%. The value of the total investment in Barings Corporate Investors increased from $9,000 to $19,000 a change of $10,000 quarter over quarter.        Advertisement






 As of the end of the quarter Bank Of America Corp /de/ had acquired  a total of 6,912 shares growing its holdings by 6.4%. The value of the company’s investment in Barings Corporate Investors went from $1,840,000 to $2,068,000 increasing 12.4% quarter to quarter. Greenwich Investment Management, Inc. trimmed its holdings by shedding 8,080 shares a decrease of 18.2% as of 06/30/2016. Greenwich Investment Management, Inc. currently owns 36,237 shares with a value of $651,000. The value of the position overall is down by 13.5%.
 In the market the company is trading up by 0.26% since yesterday’s close of $15.51.  Shares are trading at $15.55 which is marginally higher than $15.14, the stock’s 50 day moving average and which is a tad above the 200 day moving average of $15.19.  The 50 day moving average went up by +2.72% and the 200 day average went up by +2.36%. 
 Barings Corporate Investors (the Trust), formerly Babson Capital Corporate Investors, launched on September 13, 1985, is a closed-end management investment company. The Trust?s principal investments are privately placed, below-investment grade, long- term debt obligations with equity features such as common stock, warrants, conversion rights, or other equity features and, occasionally, preferred stocks. It typically purchases these investments, which are not publicly tradable, directly from their issuers in private placement transactions. These investments are typically mezzanine debt instruments with accompanying private equity securities made to small or middle market companies..
        Advertisement




